content:
Compare subgroups (categories or buckets) to learn how they relate to your model's goal. For example, compare sales performance between two territories ("North America" and "Europe"). Einstein Discovery displays a waterfall chart to help visualize the comparison.

To compare subgroups:

Open a Model.
Select a variable you want to investigate in the Variables panel.
In the Filter Selector, choose the first value you want to compare.
In the Filter Selector, choose the second value you want to compare.
Einstein shows a summary and waterfall chart of the comparison between the selected values.

A waterfall chart displays:

* First Explanatory Variable: gray bar representing the first variable
	+ Drivers of Outcome when First Explanatory Variable occurs
	+ Global Mean: mean for the selected First Explanatory Variable
	+ Global Count: number of observations for the selected First Explanatory Variable
	+ Outcome Variable: average Outcome Variable for this bucket (Total / Global Count)
* Second Explanatory Variable: blue bar representing the second variable
	+ Drivers of Outcome when Second Explanatory Variable occurs
	+ Global Mean: mean for the selected Second Explanatory Variable
	+ Global Count: number of observations for the selected Second Explanatory Variable
	+ Outcome Variable: average Outcome Variable for this bucket (Total / Global Count)
* Cases where first variable falls behind and outperforms
	+ Green bars reflect favorable effect on outcome, moving closer to model's goal
	+ Red bars reflect unfavorable effect on outcome, moving away from model's goal

Hover over a bar to see additional information. Some bars display:

* Drivers of Outcome when Explanatory Variable and Other Condition occurs
	+ Left Base Impact: how much this term impacts the first selected group
	+ Left Coefficient: model coefficient for interaction between this term and the first selected group
	+ Left Frequency: how often this term occurs in the first selected group
* Small Terms:
	+ Combined Impact: net impact on Outcome of all combined terms
	+ Terms Combined: number of terms combined
	+ Outcome: net effect on Outcome.
title: Comparing Subgroups in Einstein Discovery
